Assignment 5¶

In this assignment, you'll scrape text from The California Aggie and then analyze the text.

The Aggie is organized by category into article lists. For example, there's a Campus News list, Arts & Culture list, and Sports list. Notice that each list has multiple pages, with a maximum of 15 articles per page.

The goal of exercises 1.1 - 1.3 is to scrape articles from the Aggie for analysis in exercise 1.4.

Exercise 1.1. Write a function that extracts all of the links to articles in an Aggie article list. The function should:

  • Have a parameter url for the URL of the article list.

  • Have a parameter page for the number of pages to fetch links from. The default should be 1.

  • Return a list of aricle URLs (each URL should be a string).

Test your function on 2-3 different categories to make sure it works.

Hints:

  • Be polite to The Aggie and save time by setting up requests_cache before you write your function.

  • Start by getting your function to work for just 1 page. Once that works, have your function call itself to get additional pages.

  • You can use lxml.html or BeautifulSoup to scrape HTML. Choose one and use it throughout the entire assignment.

In [3]:
def aggielinkextract(url,page = 1):
    """
    Takes an the article list url and then extracts all the URL links from the page to be used later
    change page in order to increase the amount that it is looking for
    """
    if 'page' not in url and not url.endswith('/'):
        url = url + '/page/'
    elif 'page' not in url:
        url = url+'page/'
    finallist = []
    for x in xrange(page):
        urltemp = url+str(x+1)
        link = requests.get(urltemp)
        linkhtml = link.text
        thehtml = BeautifulSoup(linkhtml,'html.parser')
        content = thehtml.find_all(name='h2',attrs = {'class':'entry-title'})
        for x in xrange(len(content)):
            deeper = content[x]
            name = deeper.find_all('a')[0].attrs['href']
            finallist.append(str(name))
    return finallist

Hints:

  • The author line is always the last line of the last paragraph.

  • Python 2 displays some Unicode characters as \uXXXX. For instance, \u201c is a left-facing quotation mark. You can convert most of these to ASCII characters with the method call (on a string)

    .translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })

    If you're curious about these characters, you can look them up on this page, or read more about what Unicode is.

In [7]:
def aggietextextract(url):
    """
    Takes in a url and returns the name of the article, the text in the article, the author name, and the url
    will return as a dictionary with the entries 'author', 'text', 'title', 'url'
    """
    finaldict = {'url':url, 'author':[],'text':[],'title':[]}
    link = requests.get(url)
    linkhtml = link.text
    thehtml = BeautifulSoup(linkhtml,'html.parser')
    content = thehtml.find_all(name='h1',attrs = {'class':'entry-title'})
    title = str(content[0].text.encode('ascii', 'ignore'))
    finaldict['title'] = title
    content = thehtml.find_all(name='div',attrs = {'itemprop':'articleBody'})[0]
    content = content.find_all(name='p')
    body = ""
    for x in xrange(len(content)-1):
        body = body + content[x].text + ' '
    body = body.translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })
    author = content[len(content)-1].text
    if not author.startswith('Written'):
        endlist =author.split('\n')
        author = endlist[len(endlist)-1]
        for x in xrange(len(endlist)-1):
            body = body + endlist[x] + ' '
    finaldict['text']=body
    finaldict['author'] = author
    return(finaldict)

tokenize = nltk.word_tokenize

def stem(tokens,stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem):
    return [stemmer(w.lower()) for w in tokens] 

def lemmatize(text):
    """
    Extract simple lemmas based on tokenization and stemming
    Input: string
    Output: list of strings (lemmata)
    """
    return stem(tokenize(text))
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(tokenizer=lemmatize,stop_words="english",smooth_idf=True,norm=None)

City Articles and Campus Articles¶

To test this, I checked to see how many articles were the same between the city and campus articles. This gave me 0 meaning that none were the same meaning that the two are exclusive completely. We also have a low sim on average, meaning that a large diverse number of words are used and that they are not particularly similar completely.

We also see in the titles that UC is more important than Davis in the campus vs the city news with the city news more focused on police, food, and the Yolo county as a whole.

In the bodies, we see again that UC is more important than Davis overall and that for the campus, Student is one of the major words overall while for the city, city is much larger. Community is very similar though which is good to see that being cared about for both the city and Campus news that there is a connection between the campus and the city and a care for the community. They both though seem to have similar diversity in words though with no big similarity in that department.

Representation of the Aggie¶

I do not think this is representative of the Aggie since this is just the 60 most recent articles, a better representation would take random articles from across the site, not just the campus and city news sections and randomly across time. This dataset only predicts those that are recent articles in regards to campus and city news unfortunately
